All these words may denote the repetition of an action, and hence eliam alque eliam means ‘again and again.'

4. But the expression ‘is the man even now awake?' may imply ‘is the man, having been for some time asleep, yet awake?’ and hence ‘even now' may indicate that things having continued in one particular state for some time, this state has been or is likely to be ‘interrupted Questions such as the above are frequently put with some degree of surprise or impatience, and this is often rendered emphatic in English by the introduction of a negative. Thus, ‘is the man not even now awake ?' ‘is the man not going even now to hold his tongue ?' and hence ‘even now’ is often equivalent to ‘at last!

We may proceed to give examples of eliam under each of the above heads.
